{"title_page": "Deborah Paredez", "text_new": "{{Infobox writer <!-- For more information see [[:Template:Infobox Writer/doc]]. --> \n| name          = Deborah Paredez\n| image         = Paredez-Author Photo-Books.jpg\n| image_size    = \n| alt           = \n| caption       = \n| pseudonym     = \n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = 1970\n| birth_place   = San Antonio, Texas\n| death_date    = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| death_place   = \n| resting_place = \n| occupation    = Professor, poet\n| language      = English, Spanish\n| nationality   = American\n| citizenship   = American\n| education     = \n| alma_mater    = BA, [[Trinity University (Texas)|Trinity University]];<br> PhD, [[Northwestern University]]\n| period        = \n| genre         = Poetry, Essays\n| subject       = \n| movement      = \n| notableworks  = \n| spouse        =\n| partner       = \n| children      = \n| relatives     = \n| awards        = \n| signature     = \n| signature_alt = \n| module        =\n| website       = \n| portaldisp    = \n}}\n\n'''Deborah Paredez''' (born December 19, 1970) is an American poet, scholar, and cultural critic. She is the author of the poetry collections, ''Year of the Dog'' and ''This Side of Skin,'' and the critical study, ''[[Selenidad]]: [[Selena]], Latinos, and the Performance of Memory.''  She is Co-Founder (and served as Co-Director from 2009-2019)  of [[CantoMundo]], a national organization that supports Latinx poets and poetry.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cantomundo.org/about-us|title=About Us {{!}} CantoMundo|website=www.cantomundo.org|language=en|access-date=2018-04-10}}</ref> She lives in New York City where she is a professor of creative writing and ethnic studies at [[Columbia University]].\n\n==Personal life==\n\nParedez was born and raised in [[San Antonio]], Texas.<ref name=\"Interview with Paredez\">[http://www.acccreativewriting.com/apd/?p=291], Interview with Paredez by the Austin Poets Directory. Retrieved June 6, 2012.</ref>  She has lived and worked in Seattle, Chicago, Crested Butte, Oaxaca City, Austin, Paris, and New York City.  She is married to the historian [[Frank Andre Guridy]].<ref>[http://www.chicanopedia.org/article.php?articleid=20&categoryid=46&subid], Chicanopedia Article. Retrieved June 6, 2012.</ref>\n\n==Professional life==\n\nParedez earned a BA in English Literature from [[Trinity University (Texas)|Trinity University]] in 1993 and a doctorate from the Interdisciplinary Ph.D. in Theatre and Drama (IPTD) program at [[Northwestern University]] in 2002.  She has taught at [[Vassar College]] (2000-2003), [[University of Texas at Austin]] (2003-2016), [[Universit\u00e9 Sorbonne nouvelle]] (2014), and [[Columbia University]] (2015\u2013present). Along with [[Norma Elia Cant\u00fa]], Pablo Martinez, Celeste Mendoza, and [[Carmen Tafolla]], Paredez co-founded [[CantoMundo]] in 2009.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.austinchronicle.com/books/2011-07-01/come-together/|title=Come Together|access-date=2018-04-10|language=en-US}}</ref>   She writes essays about American performance, Latina/o culture, and divas.  Her poetry is influenced by contemporary American poets including [[Natasha Trethewey]], [[Sharon Olds]], and [[A.E. Stallings]].<ref name=\"Austin Poets Directory\">[http://www.acccreativewriting.com/apd/?p=291], Austin Poets Directory.</ref>\n\n==Published Work==\n\nHer poetry collection, ''Year of the Dog'' (BOA Editions 2020), was listed as a \"New and Notable Poetry Book\" by ''[[The New York Times]]'' and described as \"candid and chilling\" by ''[[Ms. Magazine]]''. Her poetry collection, ''This Side of Skin,'' was published by Wings Press in 2002.  Her scholarly book, ''[[Selenidad]]: [[Selena]], Latinos, and the Performance of Memory,'' was published by Duke University Press in 2009 and was the recipient of the National Association of Chicana/o Studies Book Award-Honorable Mention and the Latino Studies Book Award-Honorable Mention.<ref>{{Citation|last=duppublicity|title=Deborah Paredez talks about Selenidad|date=2009-12-07|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=AsxqQjU3EBg|accessdate=2018-04-10}}</ref>\n\nHer essays and poems have appeared in ''[[Poetry magazine|Poetry]]'', ''[[The New York Times]]'', ''[[Los Angeles Review of Books]]'', ''[[Poet Lore]]'', ''Crab Orchard Review,'' ''Callaloo,'' and ''Theatre Journal.'' <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.poetryfoundation.org/poets/deborah-paredez|title=Deborah Paredez|date=2018-04-10|website=Poetry Foundation|language=en-us|others=Poetry Foundation|access-date=2018-04-10}}</ref>  Her work has also been anthologized in ''The Gulf Stream: Poems of the Gulf Coast'' (Snake Nation Press 2014), ''Beyond El Barrio: Everyday Life in Latina/o America'' (NYU Press 2010), ''Women and Migration in the US-Mexico Borderlands'' (Duke University Press 2007), ''The Wind Shifts: New Latino Poetry'' (University of Arizona University Press 2007), ''Floricanto S\u00ed! A Collection of Latina Poetry'' (Penguin 1998), and ''Daughters of the Fifth Sun: A Collection of Latina Fiction and Poetry'' (Riverhead 1995).<ref>[http://www.chicanopedia.org/article.php?articleid=20&categoryid=46&subid], Chicanopedia article.</ref>\n\n==Works==\n* {{cite book | last=Paredez | first=D. | title=Year of the Dog | publisher=BOA Editions | year=2020 | isbn=978-1-950774-01-2 | url=https://www.boaeditions.org/products/year-of-the-dog | ref=harv | access-date=2020-04-13}}\n* {{cite book | last=Paredez | first=D. | title=This Side of Skin | publisher=Wings Press | year=2002 | isbn=978-0-930324-68-1 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VJdyAAAAMAAJ | ref=harv | access-date=2018-04-10}}\n* {{cite book | last=Paredez | first=D. | title=Selenidad: Selena, Latinos, and the Performance of Memory | publisher=Duke University Press | series=e-Duke books scholarly collection. | year=2009 | isbn=978-0-8223-9089-3 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=E0ahwKxObQoC | ref=harv | access-date=2018-04-10}}\n\n==References==\n\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n* [http://deborahparedez.com Author Website]\n* [https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/31/books/review/new-this-week.html]\n* [https://msmagazine.com/2020/01/01/reads-for-the-rest-of-us-feminist-books-coming-out-in-2020/]\n* [https://www.npr.org/2019/09/17/759193674/celia-cruz-the-voice-of-experience]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20160710184310/http://arts.columbia.edu/writing/faculty/deborah-paredez Columbia University School of the Arts Writing Program]\n* [http://podbay.fm/show/270054093/e/1346738400?autostart=1 Poetry Foundation Podcast Featuring Deborah Paredez]\n* [http://lareviewofbooks.org/contributor/deborah-paredez We Can Be Heroes: Poetry at the Olympics]\n* [http://learning.blogs.nytimes.com/2013/06/06/poetry-pairing-the-gulf-1987/?_php=true&_type=blogs&_r=0 ''The New York Times'' Poetry Pairing]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Paredez, Deborah}}\n[[Category:1970 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Northwestern University alumni]]\n[[Category:Columbia University faculty]]\n[[Category:University of Texas at Austin faculty]]\n[[Category:Vassar College faculty]]\n[[Category:People from San Antonio]]\n[[Category:American women poets]]\n[[Category:21st-century American poets]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox writer <!-- For more information see [[:Template:Infobox Writer/doc]]. --> \n| name          = Deborah Paredez\n| image         = Paredez-Author Photo-Books.jpg\n| image_size    = \n| alt           = \n| caption       = \n| pseudonym     = \n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = 1970\n| birth_place   = San Antonio, Texas\n| death_date    = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| death_place   = \n| resting_place = \n| occupation    = Professor, poet\n| language      = English, Spanish\n| nationality   = American\n| citizenship   = American\n| education     = \n| alma_mater    = BA, [[Trinity University (Texas)|Trinity University]];<br> PhD, [[Northwestern University]]\n| period        = \n| genre         = Poetry, Essays\n| subject       = \n| movement      = \n| notableworks  = \n| spouse        =\n| partner       = \n| children      = \n| relatives     = \n| awards        = \n| signature     = \n| signature_alt = \n| module        =\n| website       = \n| portaldisp    = \n}}\n\n'''Deborah Paredez''' (born December 19, 1970) is an American poet, scholar, and cultural critic. She is the author of the poetry collections, ''Year of the Dog'' and ''This Side of Skin,'' and the critical study, ''[[Selenidad]]: [[Selena]], Latinos, and the Performance of Memory.''  She is Co-Founder (and served as Co-Director from 2009-2019)  of [[CantoMundo]], a national organization that supports Latinx poets and poetry.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cantomundo.org/about-us|title=About Us {{!}} CantoMundo|website=www.cantomundo.org|language=en|access-date=2018-04-10}}</ref> She lives in New York City where she is a professor of creative writing and ethnic studies at [[Columbia University]].\n\n==Personal life==\n\nParedez was born and raised in [[San Antonio]], Texas.<ref name=\"Interview with Paredez\">[http://www.acccreativewriting.com/apd/?p=291], Interview with Paredez by the Austin Poets Directory. Retrieved June 6, 2012.</ref>  She has lived and worked in Seattle, Chicago, Crested Butte, Oaxaca City, Austin, Paris, and New York City.  She is married to the historian [[Frank Andre Guridy]].<ref>[http://www.chicanopedia.org/article.php?articleid=20&categoryid=46&subid], Chicanopedia Article. Retrieved June 6, 2012.</ref>\n\n==Professional life==\n\nParedez earned a BA in English Literature from [[Trinity University (Texas)|Trinity University]] in 1993 and a doctorate from the Interdisciplinary Ph.D. in Theatre and Drama (IPTD) program at [[Northwestern University]] in 2002.  She has taught at [[Vassar College]] (2000-2003), [[University of Texas at Austin]] (2003-2016), [[Universit\u00e9 Sorbonne nouvelle]] (2014), and [[Columbia University]] (2015\u2013present). Along with [[Norma Elia Cant\u00fa]], Pablo Martinez, Celeste Mendoza, and [[Carmen Tafolla]], Paredez co-founded [[CantoMundo]] in 2009.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.austinchronicle.com/books/2011-07-01/come-together/|title=Come Together|access-date=2018-04-10|language=en-US}}</ref>   She writes essays about American performance, Latina/o culture, and divas.  Her poetry is influenced by contemporary American poets including [[Natasha Trethewey]], [[Sharon Olds]], and [[A.E. Stallings]].<ref name=\"Austin Poets Directory\">[http://www.acccreativewriting.com/apd/?p=291], Austin Poets Directory.</ref>\n\n==Published Work==\n\nHer poetry collection, ''Year of the Dog'' (BOA Editions 2020), was listed as a \"New and Notable Poetry Book\" by ''[[The New York Times]]'' and described as \"candid and chilling' by ''[[Ms. Magazine]]''. Her poetry collection, ''This Side of Skin,'' was published by Wings Press in 2002.  Her scholarly book, ''[[Selenidad]]: [[Selena]], Latinos, and the Performance of Memory,'' was published by Duke University Press in 2009 and was the recipient of the National Association of Chicana/o Studies Book Award-Honorable Mention and the Latino Studies Book Award-Honorable Mention.<ref>{{Citation|last=duppublicity|title=Deborah Paredez talks about Selenidad|date=2009-12-07|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=AsxqQjU3EBg|accessdate=2018-04-10}}</ref>\n\nHer essays and poems have appeared in ''[[Poetry magazine|Poetry]]'', ''[[The New York Times]]'', ''[[Los Angeles Review of Books]]'', ''[[Poet Lore]]'', ''Crab Orchard Review,'' ''Callaloo,'' and ''Theatre Journal.'' <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.poetryfoundation.org/poets/deborah-paredez|title=Deborah Paredez|date=2018-04-10|website=Poetry Foundation|language=en-us|others=Poetry Foundation|access-date=2018-04-10}}</ref>  Her work has also been anthologized in ''The Gulf Stream: Poems of the Gulf Coast'' (Snake Nation Press 2014), ''Beyond El Barrio: Everyday Life in Latina/o America'' (NYU Press 2010), ''Women and Migration in the US-Mexico Borderlands'' (Duke University Press 2007), ''The Wind Shifts: New Latino Poetry'' (University of Arizona University Press 2007), ''Floricanto S\u00ed! A Collection of Latina Poetry'' (Penguin 1998), and ''Daughters of the Fifth Sun: A Collection of Latina Fiction and Poetry'' (Riverhead 1995).<ref>[http://www.chicanopedia.org/article.php?articleid=20&categoryid=46&subid], Chicanopedia article.</ref>\n\n==Works==\n* {{cite book | last=Paredez | first=D. | title=Year of the Dog | publisher=BOA Editions | year=2020 | isbn=978-1-950774-01-2 | url=https://www.boaeditions.org/products/year-of-the-dog | ref=harv | access-date=2020-04-13}}\n* {{cite book | last=Paredez | first=D. | title=This Side of Skin | publisher=Wings Press | year=2002 | isbn=978-0-930324-68-1 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VJdyAAAAMAAJ | ref=harv | access-date=2018-04-10}}\n* {{cite book | last=Paredez | first=D. | title=Selenidad: Selena, Latinos, and the Performance of Memory | publisher=Duke University Press | series=e-Duke books scholarly collection. | year=2009 | isbn=978-0-8223-9089-3 | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=E0ahwKxObQoC | ref=harv | access-date=2018-04-10}}\n\n==References==\n\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n* [http://deborahparedez.com Author Website]\n* [https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/31/books/review/new-this-week.html]\n* [https://msmagazine.com/2020/01/01/reads-for-the-rest-of-us-feminist-books-coming-out-in-2020/]\n* [https://www.npr.org/2019/09/17/759193674/celia-cruz-the-voice-of-experience]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20160710184310/http://arts.columbia.edu/writing/faculty/deborah-paredez Columbia University School of the Arts Writing Program]\n* [http://podbay.fm/show/270054093/e/1346738400?autostart=1 Poetry Foundation Podcast Featuring Deborah Paredez]\n* [http://lareviewofbooks.org/contributor/deborah-paredez We Can Be Heroes: Poetry at the Olympics]\n* [http://learning.blogs.nytimes.com/